{{redirect|Trial jury|the form of trial involving a petit jury|Jury trial}}
In [[common law]], a '''petit jury''' (or '''trial jury''') hears the [[evidence]] in a [[trial]] as presented by both the [[plaintiff]] (petitioner) and the [[defendant]] (respondent). After hearing the evidence and often [[jury instructions]] from the [[judge]], the group retires for [[deliberation]], to consider a verdict. The majority required for a verdict varies. In some cases it must be unanimous, while in other jurisdictions it may be a majority or [[supermajority]]. A jury that is unable to come to a verdict is referred to as a [[hung jury]]. The size of the jury varies; in [[Criminal law|criminal cases]] involving serious felonies there are usually 12 jurors, although Scotland uses 15. A number of countries that are not in the English common law tradition have quasi-juries on which lay judges or jurors and professional judges deliberate together regarding criminal cases. However, the common law trial jury is the most common type of jury system.<ref name="flsd_Unit">{{Cite web| title = United States District Court: Petit Jury| work = flsd.uscourts.gov| accessdate = 2016-04-19| url = https://www.flsd.uscourts.gov/?page_id=1136}}</ref><ref name="usco_Type">{{Cite web| title = Types of Juries| work = United States Courts| accessdate = 2016-04-19| url = http://www.uscourts.gov/services-forms/jury-service/types-juries}}</ref>

In [[Civil law (common law)|civil cases]] many trials require fewer than twelve jurors.  Juries are almost never used in civil cases outside the United States and Canada.  Other states with a common law tradition sometimes use them in defamation cases, in cases involving a governmental eminent domain power, and in cases involving alleged wrongful conviction.  Civil law countries generally do not use civil juries.  Civil juries are available in the United States and Canada in almost all cases where the only remedy sought is money damages.<ref name="judi_NewJ">{{Cite web| title = New Jersey Courts| work = judiciary.state.nj.us| accessdate = 2016-04-19| url = http://www.judiciary.state.nj.us/hudson/jury/jurypetit.html}}</ref>

