In the [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]], '''Shakkanakku''', {{Lang-akk|{{cuneiform|𒇽𒃻𒃶𒅘𒆪}}}}, was a title designating a military governor.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jhbSbuplQ28C&pg=PA113|title=Historical Dictionary of Mesopotamia|author=Gwendolyn Leick| page=113}}</ref> [[Mari, Syria|Mari]] was ruled by a dynasty of hereditary Shakkanakkus which was originally set by the Akkadian empire and gained independence following Akkad's collapse.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q8Z7AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA18|title=Ancient Syria: A Three Thousand Year History|author=Trevor Bryce| page=18}}</ref> The title also existed in [[Qatna]] in the 14th century BC,{{sfn|Gromova|2007|p=300}} and [[Dilmun]] under the [[Kassites]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ncfIAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA35|title=The Persian Gulf in History|author= L. Potter| page=35}}</ref>
