'''Susan Ariel Aaronson''' is an [[United States|American]] [[author]], [[public speaker]] and an [[academic]] whose works are centred on the relationship between economic change and [[human rights]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.institutdesameriques.fr/sites/default/files/fichiers_lies/susan_ariel_aaronson.pdf|title= Susan Ariel Aaronson|publisher=Institute de Ameriques|date=|accessdate=6 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/tipsheets/morning-trade/2015/11/morning-trade-behsudi-211359|title=Reichert: TPP review tops W&M panel to-do list|publisher=Politico|last=Behsudi|first=Adam|date=19 November 2015|accessdate=6 December 2015}}</ref> Aaronson currently works as a research professor at the [[Elliott School of International Affairs]] after serving as a fellow of the [[World Trade Institute]] from 2008&ndash;2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elliott.gwu.edu/aaronson|title=Susan Ariel Aaronson|publisher=[[Elliott School of International Affairs]]|date=|accessdate=6 December 2015}}</ref>
==Education== <ref>[https://elliott.gwu.edu/sites/elliott.gwu.edu/files/Susan%20Aaronson%202015cv.doc C.V.]</ref> *B.A. History- Magna Cum Laude and [[Phi Beta Kappa]], [[Binghamton University]], *M.I.A. and M.A., Political Science and International Affairs, [[Columbia University]], *M.A. and Ph.D, Economic and Business History, [[Johns Hopkins University]], 1993
==Published works== *''For the People, But Not by the People: A History of the International Trade Organization (ITO)'' (1993) *''Trade Policy Making'' (2001) *''The Lost History of Public Efforts to Shape Globalization.'' (2002) *''Trade Imbalance: The Struggle to Weigh Human Rights Concerns in Trade Policymaking.'' (2007) *''Trade and the American Dream: A Social History of Postwar Trade Policy.'' (2015)
